Article 4 of the Statutes of the [[International_Red_Cross_and_Red_Crescent_Movement|International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement]], adopted by the 25th International Conference of the Red Cross at [[Geneva|Geneva]] in October 1986 and amended by the 26th International Conference of the Red Cross at Geneva in December 1995 states that<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.icrc.org/web/eng/siteeng0.nsf/html/6ERK5H | title = Conditions for recognition of national societies | publisher = International Committee of the Red Cross | date = 2005-07-29}}</ref>:

In order to be recognized by the [[ICRC|ICRC]] as a national society, it shall meet the following conditions:

<blockquote>''1. Be constituted on the territory of an independent [[Sovereign_state|State]] where the [[Geneva_Convention|Geneva Convention]] for the Amelioration of the Condition of the Wounded and Sick in Armed Forces in the Field is in force.''</blockquote>

(Currently, Taiwan (the [[Republic_of_China|Republic of China]]) is recognized as an independent state by the [[ICRC|ICRC]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.icrc.org/web/eng/siteeng0.nsf/htmlall/tracing_offices?opendocument| title = Tracing offices of recognized Red Cross and Red Crescent National Societies| publisher = ICRC | date = 2009-01-05}}</ref>.)

<blockquote>''2. Be the only National Red Cross or Red Crescent Society of the said State and be directed by a central body which shall alone be competent to represent it in its dealings with other components of the Movement.''</blockquote>

(Currently, the Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) is the only National Red Cross in the territories under its control and there is only one central body.)

<blockquote>''3. Be duly recognized by the legal government of its country on the basis of the [[Geneva_Conventions|Geneva Conventions]] and of the national legislation as a voluntary aid society, auxiliary to the public authorities in the humanitarian field.''</blockquote>

(Currently, the Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria.)

<blockquote>''4. Have an autonomous status which allows it to operate in conformity with the Fundamental Principles of the Movement.''</blockquote>

(Currently, The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria. The 1955 law provides for the autonomy of the organization.)

<blockquote>''5. Use the name and emblem of the Red Cross or Red Crescent in conformity with the [[Geneva_Convention|Geneva Convention]]s.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria.)

<blockquote>''6. Be so organized as to be able to fulfill the tasks defined in its own statutes, including the preparation in peace time for its statutory tasks in case of armed conflict.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria.)

<blockquote>''7. Extend its activities to the entire territory of the State.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria. Presently, the [[Republic_of_China|Republic of China]] controls the islands of [[Taiwan|Taiwan]], [[Penghu|Penghu]], [[Jinmen|Jinmen]] and [[Mazu_Islands|Mazu Islands]].)

<blockquote>''8. Recruit its voluntary members and its staff without consideration of race, sex, class, religion or political opinions.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria.)

<blockquote>''9. Adhere to the present Statutes, share in the fellowship which unites the components of the Movement and co-operate with them.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria. It is able to adheres to the Statutes, since Taiwan (the [[Republic_of_China|Republic of China]]) is recognized by the [[ICRC|ICRC]] as a State<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.icrc.org/web/eng/siteeng0.nsf/htmlall/tracing_offices?opendocument| title = Tracing offices of recognized Red Cross and Red Crescent National Societies| publisher = ICRC | date = 2009-01-05}}</ref>.)

<blockquote>''10. Respect the Fundamental Principles of the Movement and be guided in its work by the principles of international humanitarian law.''</blockquote>

(The Red Cross Society of the Republic of China (Taiwan) meets this criteria.)
